  "summary": "This file describes a small command-line product called **diffdoc**.\n\n### What the product is for\nIts purpose is to **turn code changes in a repository into plain-English business explanations**. In other words, it helps people understand what changed in a codebase without needing to read the code itself.\n\n### What users can do\n- Run a tool named **`diffdoc`** from the command line.\n- Run a related tool named **`diffdoc-mcp`** for integration with another system.\n- Use it on a machine that has **Node.js version 22 or newer** installed.\n\n### What gets included in the product\nWhen the software is packaged for release, it includes:\n- the compiled program in the `dist` folder\n- the main documentation file\n- the license\n- an example configuration file\n\n### How it is built and released\nThe project is written in TypeScript and must be compiled before use.\n- **`build`**: converts the source code into runnable JavaScript\n- **`clean`**: removes the built output\n- **`start`**: builds the project and then runs it\n- **`prepare`**: automatically builds the project when it is being prepared for publishing or installation\n\n### What external capabilities it relies on\nThe tool depends on several libraries that support:\n- command-line interaction\n- reading and ignoring files in a repository\n- connecting to OpenAI services\n- working with Git history\n- storing and searching vector-based data\n- validating data and settings\n\n### Business impact\nFrom a business perspective, this package is designed to:\n- reduce the time needed to understand code changes\n- make technical changes easier to explain to non-technical people\n- improve visibility into what changed in a repository\n- support both direct command-line use and integration into other tools\n\n### Visible outcome for the user\nA user who installs and runs this package should see:\n- a command-line tool available as `diffdoc`\n- a second command-line entry point available as `diffdoc-mcp`\n- generated plain-English summaries of repository changes rather than raw code details",
